indicate that there is a resource with reference EPR in Ï (otherwise EPR Ï). We use Ï(EPR) to represent the
current value (in Ï) of resource EPR. Furthermore, with Ï[k/EPR] we represent the change of the property value
of EPR, which is now assigned to k âˆˆ Z. We also use function eval(expr, v) to evaluate an expression according
to the values of variables v, v âˆˆ ZVar . By v[expr/w] we denote the change of variable w for the evaluation of
expr. Function Add subs(Ï, EPR, O, cond, A1 ) is used to add a new subscriber O for the resource EPR in Ï. In the
event that object O were already subscribed to EPR, we replace its old notiï¬cation condition and activity by the
newly indicated ones. We also use function Remove subs(Ï), which is used to remove from Ï those subscriptions
which have been notiï¬ed, because their associated conditions have occurred. Formalizations of these deï¬nitions
are immediate, so we omit them.
Let us now describe the transitions: null transitions are used to solve the alternatives and loops, depending on
the guard evaluation. They are also used in a sequence of frames to activate the second frame when the ï¬rst has
terminated. The rules deï¬ning null transitions are shown in Table 1. In these rules we denote by nil the frame
(r1 : nil, . . . , rn : nil).
In order to deï¬ne action transitions we ï¬rst need to deï¬ne these transitions for the activities inside the frames,
which follow the syntax:
a
(A, (v, Ï)) âˆ’â†’ (A , (v , Ï ))
where a âˆˆ Alph, where this alphabet of actions can be easily derived from the rules.
Rules deï¬ning the action transitions for the activities are shown in Table 2. In this table, notiï¬cations and
synchronizations are not yet considered, they will be considered later, when deï¬ning the action transition rules at
the frame level (Table 3). Rules in Table 2 are very intuitive, expressing the sequential evolution of the activities
performed by a single object.
