A frame action transition has the following form: (F, s) âˆ’â†’ (F , s ), where a âˆˆ Alph, and they are deï¬ned by
the rules in Table 3. The evolution by executing an action labeled with a message identiï¬er m is obtained from a
synchronization between two objects that communicate using this message identiï¬er (rule Syncr). Notiï¬cations
are not included in the case of rule Syncr, since Ï has not changed. Rule Obj captures the single evolution of an
object within a frame, but notice that in this case some notiï¬cations may appear, as a consequence of the possible
change in the resource property values. Notiï¬cations are formally deï¬ned as activities launched upon the fulï¬lling
of the conditions indicated by the resource subscribers. These activities (handlers in the WSRF terminology) with
the activity that the corresponding subscriber was executing when the subscription condition was fulï¬lled. Thus,
function Nl (Ï) is introduced in rule Obj in Table 3, which unfolds the activities that every object should execute
before performing its next local activity. Nl (Ï) can be empty, in the event that no activity should be launched
for object i, in this case we take Nl (Ï); Al = Al . Otherwise, Nl (Ï) = {Al1 ; . . . ; Alk | 1 â‰¤ l1 â‰¤ ... â‰¤ lK â‰¤ r, âˆ€ j âˆˆ
